# Runtime process and bootstrap secrets

## Rule

Bootstrap-only credentials must be scoped to the bootstrap operation and removed
before starting or reloading long-lived application processes.

## Common hazards

- Process managers inheriting shell environment during reload.
- Admin database URLs exported before app start.
- Migration superuser tokens left in `.env` files.
- CI secrets printed in logs.
- Build-time secrets baked into frontend bundles.
- Local override files committed by mistake.

## Requirements

1. Pass privileged credentials only into the subprocess that needs them.
2. `unset` or avoid exporting bootstrap secrets before runtime start/reload.
3. Runtime `.env` files should contain least-privilege credentials only.
4. Bootstrap scripts must grant privileges to the role that will own future
   objects, not only the current admin session.
5. Health checks should fail if runtime lacks required least-privilege access.
6. Logs must redact credentials.

## Pre-commit check

- [ ] Bootstrap secret is not present in runtime process environment.
- [ ] Least-privilege runtime credentials are documented and used.
- [ ] Secrets are not printed or bundled.
- [ ] Privilege grants apply to future objects where needed.
